Prolactin (and prolactinomas)

Search prolactinoma.

Prolactin physiology:

  • Prolactin is secreted by lactotroph cells in the anterior pituitary.

  • Level of secretion of prolantin due to a given stimulus proportional to background hyperplasia of lactotrophs which is driven by oestrogen.

  • Prolactin secretion by lactotrophs is under tonic inhibition of dopamine (which acts on D2 receptors of the lactotrophs) secreted by the tuberoinfundibular pathway, originating in the arcuate nucleus of the hypothalamus.

  • Dopaminergic inhibition is reduced in response to nipple stimulation, as part of the let down reflex. (this also involved oxytocin secretion from the posterior pituiary which causes the myoepithelial cells in the milk ducts to contract.)

  • Prolacting inhibits GnRH release from the hypothalamus; This causes lactation amenorrhoea while breast feeding and also decreased sexual function in prolactinoma.

  • Hyperprolactinaemia causes amenorrhoea.

  • Oestrogen tends to increase prolactin levels.

  • Source

    • Adenomas are usually composed solely of lactotroph cells.

    Features of prolactinomas which help to identify a prolactinomas as the cause for hyperprolactinaemia

    • Level of Prolactin rise is proportional to the size of the prolactinoma.
      • microadenoma - upto 200 ng/ml
      • 1-2 cm -> upto 1000ng/ml
      • If the PRL level is less than the size of the lesion would suggest, it could be a poorly differentiated lactotroph adenoma or a cystic adenoma.
      • lactotroph adenomas are efficient: so even microadenomas can produce a clinically significant amount of prolacting without causing pressure symptoms.
      • Usually, macroadenomas as the ones which cause pressure symptoms. Microadenomas don't usually cause compressive symptoms.
      • hyperprolactinaemia due to mass effect compressing the pituitary will respond to dopamin agonist therapy just like a lactotroph adenoma. Therfore, response to dopamine therapy doesn't confirm a lactotroph adenoma. -Harrison's
      • Olanzapine is a well-known cause of hyperprolactinaemia AND hypogonadotrophic hypogonadism
      • Tumours of hypothalamus, pituitary stalk or pituitary itself
      • Infitrative diseaseses -> [[Sarcoidosis]], malignant invasion.

[!INFO] Metabolic diseases predisposing to stroke:

  1. CADASIL
  2. MELAS
  3. Fabry Disease
  4. homocystinuria
  1. Ranolazine: Newer addition - late sodium channel blocker.
    1. inhibits late sodium current and hence indirectly reduces intracellular calcium and force of contraction,without affecting heart rate;

      1. Intracellular calcium overload is believed to be critical to the mechanism of decreased left ventricular relaxation caused by ischemia and reperfusion. Elevated left ventricular diastolic wall tension compromises myocardial blood flow even further. Additionally, calcium overload has adverse effects on myocardial electrical activity predisposing to ventricular tachycardia Source

  • retinal and central nervous system (CNS) hemangioblastomas (blood vessel tumors), pheochromocytomas, multiple cysts in the pancreas and kidneys, and an increased risk for malignant transformation of renal cysts into renal cell carcinoma.
  • Also phaeochromocytoma
    • Commonest type are functioning prolactinomas.
    • Incidence: Prolactinoma > non function > GH secreting > ACTH secreting.
    • Of the functioning ones prolactinomas are the commonest.

Pituitary microadenoma is usually an incidental finding on MRI head. Patients are asymptomatic unless the tumor is hormonally active.

Prolactinoma

Presentation

  • Men present with impotence, loss of libido,
  • CNS compression signs.
